topic.title: Link Status Retrieve Command

body.p: This command retrieves the link status of the specified port(s). There are no sub-commands for this MRPC command.

This field is a 48-bit bitmap indicating the requested ports. Setting a bit to 1 indicates that the corresponding port's link status should be retrieved, with bit 0 corresponding to port 0, bit 1 corresponding to port 1, etc. The command will return with the link status of only the requested ports, unless all bits are cleared to 0, in which case this command returns with the link status of all ports that are currently bound to a valid partition. For example:

li.p: Port Bitmap 0x0000FFFF_FFFFFFFF requests the link status of all 48 physical ports
Port Bitmap 0x00000000_00001001 requests the link status of ports 0 and 12

body.p: The output data size varies based on the number of ports requested, with each port consuming 3 DWORDs. Unused areas of the MRPC Output Data will be initialized to 0xFF for easy identification.
The physical port ID of the port to be read. Valid range is 0 to 47.
The ID of the partition to which the port is bound. Valid range is 0 to 47. A value of 0xFF means the physical port is not bound to a partition.
The logical port ID of the port in the partition. The USP is always ID 0. All DSPs in the partition begin at ID 1. A value of 0xFF means the physical port is not bound to a partition.
The physical port ID within the stack to which the port belongs. Valid range is 0 to 7.
The ID of the stack to which this port belongs.
The link width that is configured for the port.
The link width that is negotiated during link up.
